  "prompt": "Who are some great but lesser known female Indian freedom fighters?",
  "response": "Certainly! Here are some remarkable but lesser-known female Indian freedom fighters:\n\n1. **Matangini Hazra**: An extraordinary leader who actively participated in the Quit India Movement. She led a procession of nearly six thousand protesters and continued to advance with the Indian flag even after being shot multiple times.\n\n2. **Kasturba Gandhi**: Often overshadowed by her husband Mahatma Gandhi, Kasturba was a staunch supporter of the Indian independence movement and worked alongside Gandhi in various campaigns, including those for women\u2019s rights and social reforms.\n\n3. **Rani Gaidinliu**: A Naga spiritual and political leader who led a revolt against British rule in India at the tender age of 13. She fought for the freedom of her people and was arrested and imprisoned for several years.\n\n4. **Usha Mehta**: Known for her role in organizing the Congress Radio, an underground radio station that spread nationalist messages and information during the Quit India Movement. She was arrested by British authorities for her activities.\n\n5. **Aruna Asaf Ali**: Known for hoisting the Indian National Congress flag during the Quit India Movement in 1942 at the Gowalia Tank Maidan in Mumbai, becoming an iconic figure in the struggle for independence.\n\n6. **Durgabai Deshmukh**: A prominent social reformer and freedom fighter who played a crucial role in the Civil Disobedience Movement and worked towards various social causes including women's education and rights.\n\n7. **Tara Rani Srivastava**: She and her husband participated in Gandhi's Quit India Movement. After her husband was shot, she continued to march with their community\u2019s flag and to fight for freedom.\n\nThese women, through their bravery and steadfast commitment, made significant contributions to India's independence movement and deserve recognition alongside more well-known figures.",
